The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, August 20, 2004 				 Ispat gets control of Nigerian steel plant
 PALLAB BHATTACHARYA																								Calcutta, Aug. 19: Ispat Industries Ltd has acquired the management and operational control of the Ajaokuta steel plant of Nigeria for 10 years through the UK-based holding company, Global Infrastructure Holdings Ltd.																								This is the fourth steel plant abroad, after Philippines, Libya and Bulgaria, of which the Ispat group has obtained management control.																								Ajaokuta has a steel-making capacity of 2.2 million tonnes per annum. According to sources, with the management control of the Nigerian plant, the Ispat group has entered the big league of steel makers with a total capacity of about 10 million tonnes.																								Ajaokuta also has a captive power unit, a sinter plant, a coke oven and an electric arc furnace.																								Talking to The Telegraph, Ispat group chairman P. K. Mittal said the group has set a target to achieve a 10 million-tonne capacity in the current year itself through acquisitions and a brownfield project.																								A brownfield project at Dolvi near Mumbai will raise the capacity of the plant from 2.4 million tonnes to over three million tonnes this fiscal.																								Global Steelworks International Inc of Philippines, which has been acquired early this year, has a capacity of 1.5 million tonnes of cold-roll mill. 
